  "topic_name": "Acids, Bases and Indicators",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Acids are substances that taste sour and turn blue litmus red. Common acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl), sulfuric acid (H2SO4), and citric acid found in lemons. Bases are substances that taste bitter, feel soapy, and turn red litmus blue. Common bases include sodium hydroxide (NaOH) and calcium hydroxide (Ca(OH)2). Indicators are substances that show different colors in acidic and basic solutions. Litmus is a common indicator - red litmus turns blue in bases, and blue litmus turns red in acids. When an acid reacts with a base, they neutralize each other to form salt and water. This is called a neutralization reaction.",
